===========================================================================
CLAIM 1: n=2 and n=4 are unique (pure 2-power denominator in R_n)
===========================================================================

For even n=2m: R_{2m} = pi^m / (2^{2m} * m!)
Pure 2-power denominator iff m! is a power of 2.

    m                   m!  power of 2?  smallest odd factor
  --- -------------------- ------------ --------------------
    0                    1          YES                 none
    1                    1          YES                 none <-- R_{2} pure 2-power
    2                    2          YES                 none <-- R_{4} pure 2-power
    3                    6           no                    3
    4                   24           no                    3
    5                  120           no                    3
    6                  720           no                    3
    7                 5040           no                    3
    8                40320           no                    3
    9               362880           no                    3
   10              3628800           no                    3
   11             39916800           no                    3
   12            479001600           no                    3
   13           6227020800           no                    3
   14          87178291200           no                    3
   15        1307674368000           no                    3

For odd n=2m+1: denominator always contains (2m+1)!! which has odd factors
  n=1: R_1 = 1 (trivial)
  n=3: R_3 = pi/6, denominator 6 = 2*3 (odd factor 3)
  n=5: R_5 = pi^2/48, denominator 48 = 16*3 (odd factor 3)
  n=7: R_7 = pi^3/945 * 16, odd factors present

RESULT: n=2 (m=1, 1!=1=2^0) and n=4 (m=2, 2!=2=2^1) are the
ONLY non-trivial dimensions where R_n has a pure power-of-2 denominator.
Proof: for m>=3, m! has an odd prime factor (3 divides 3! and all higher).

